# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexander-leslie-british-army-officer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The **Scots Guards** (SG) is the regiment of Foot Guards of Scotland, and one of the five foot guard regiments of the British Army.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Its origins are as the personal bodyguard of King Charles I of England and Scotland.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Its lineage can be traced back to 1642 in the Kingdom of Scotland, although it was only placed on the English Establishment in 1686.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The regiment now known as the Scots Guards traces its origins to the **Marquis of Argyll's Royal Regiment,** a unit raised in 1642 by Archibald Campbell, 1st Marquess of Argyll in response to the 1641 Irish Rebellion.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] It served in the 1679 Covenanter rising of 1679, as well as Argyll's Rising in June 1685, after which it was expanded to two battalions.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] When the Nine Years War began in 1689, the first battalion was sent to Flanders; the second served in Ireland, and fought at the 1690 Battle of the Boyne, before joining the First in 1691.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The combined unit fought at Steenkerque and Landen, as well as the 1695 Namur.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] After the Treaty of Ryswick in 1697, the regiment returned to Scotland.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The Guards remained in Scotland during the War of the Spanish Succession; retitled **The Third Regiment of Foot Guards**, it moved to London in 1712, and did not return to Scotland for another 100 years.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] During the 1740-1748 War of the Austrian Succession, the First Battalion served at Dettingen in 1743 and Fontenoy in April 1745, a British defeat famous for the Gardes françaises and Grenadier Guards inviting each other to fire first.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Both battalions were in London during the 1745 Rising; an engraving by William Hogarth shows them marching to take up defensive positions in North London.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] However, the Jacobite army turned back at Derby, and in July 1747, the Second Battalion was sent to Flanders, where it fought at Lauffeld, before the war ended with the Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In April 1809, the 1st Battalion was sent to the Iberian Peninsula, and served in the Peninsular War in Portugal and Spain.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] It took part in the crossing of the River Douro on 12 May, an operation that ended so successfully that the French Army were in full retreat to Amarante after the actions in Oporto and its surrounding areas.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In late July 1809 the regiment took part in the Battle of Talavera, one of the bloodiest and most bitter of engagements during the war.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The 2nd Battalion's flank companies took part in the disastrous Walcheren Campaign in the Low Countries.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The 1st Battalion went on to take part in the Battle of Fuentes de Oñoro in May 1811, the Battle of Salamanca in July 1812, the Siege of San Sebastián in Summer 1813 and the Battle of the Nive in December 1813.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] At the Battle of Waterloo in June 1815, the Scots Guards were positioned on the ridge just behind Hougoumont.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Their light companies, commanded by Lieutenant-Colonel James Macdonnell, held Hougoumont Farm throughout the battle, a key defensive position on the right flank of the Allied army.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The 1st Battalion, part of the 1st (Guards) Brigade of the 1st Division, was part of the British Expeditionary Force which arrived in France in 1914.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The Battalion took part in the Battle of Mons in August 1914, the First Battle of the Marne in September 1914 and the Battle of the Aisne also in September 1914.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The 1st and 2nd Battalions then took part in the First Battle of Ypres in November 1914, the Battle of Aubers Ridge in May 1915 and the Battle of Loos in September 1915.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In July 1916 the Scots Guards took part in the first Battle of the Somme and in July 1917, the regiment began its involvement in the Battle of Passchendaele.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In March 1918 they fought at the second Battle of the Somme and in Autumn the regiment took part in the final battles of the war on the Western Front.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In April 1940, the 1st Battalion, as part of the 24th Guards Brigade, took part in its first campaign of the war, during the expedition to Norway.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In North Africa, as part of the 22nd Guards Brigade, the 2nd Battalion took part in fighting against the Italians in Egypt followed by tough fighting in Libya, then also controlled by Italy.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In North Africa, in March 1943, the 2nd Battalion took part in the defensive Battle of Medenine, after the Germans had counter-attacked the Allies.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In September 1943, the 2nd Battalion, as part of the 201st Guards Brigade of the 56th (London) Division, took part in the Landing at Salerno.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In December 1943, the 1st Battalion, as part of 24th Guards Brigade, arrived in the Italian Theatre.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] At the Battle of Monte Cassino in early 1944, the 2nd Battalion suffered heavy casualties in tough fighting.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The 1st Battalion, as part of its brigade, joined the 6th South African Armoured Division in May 1944.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The regiment took part in many fierce engagements throughout 1944, including those against the Gothic Line, a formidable defensive line.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In the years following the Second World War the Scots Guards saw action in a number of Britain's colonial wars.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In 1948, the 2nd Battalion of the Scots Guards was deployed to Malaya (now part of Malaysia) to crush a Communist-inspired and pro-independence uprising during a conflict known as the Malayan Emergency.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The battalion was involved in an incident known as the Batang Kali massacre, in which they were responsible for the execution of 24 unarmed civilians.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] By the time the battalion left Malaya in 1951 and returned home, it had lost thirteen soldiers.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] By late 1951, the 1st Battalion was deployed to Cyprus; and in February 1952, the battalion deployed to the Suez Canal Zone, Egypt.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In February 1962, the 2nd Battalion arrived in Kenya, and operated in support of the civil power during the Mau Mau Uprising.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In 1965 the 1st Battalion undertook two tours in Borneo during the Indonesian Confrontation.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Both the 1st and 2nd Battalion deployed to Northern Ireland during the Troubles in the early 1970s.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In 1992, during their time in Northern Ireland, the Scots Guards were involved in the contentious shooting of civilian Peter McBride: two soldiers were convicted of murder.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] During the Falklands War in 1982 the main force of the Scots Guards began its advance on the western side of Mount Tumbledown.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In 2004, the 1st Battalion deployed to Iraq on a 6-month posting as part of 4th Armoured Brigade.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The 4th Brigade relieved the 1st Mechanised Brigade, and joined the Multi-National Division (South East) that was under British command.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] In 2021, the 1st Battalion moved to Somme Barracks, Catterick Garrison as part of the Army 2020 Refine reforms.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] On 1 May 2022 (delayed from the originally intended 1 April 2022), soldiers in A (The London Scottish) Company, the London Regiment transferred to foot guards regiments and the company became G (Messines) Company, Scots Guards, 1st Battalion London Guards.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The Scots Guards and other Guards regiments have a long-standing connection to the Parachute Regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Guardsmen who have completed the P company selection course are transferred into the Guards Parachute Platoon, which is part of 3rd Battalion, Parachute Regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] 1 (Guards) Independent Parachute Company, who were the original Pathfinder Group of the 16th Parachute Brigade.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The Scots Guards is ranked as the third regiment in the Guards Division.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] As such, Scots Guardsmen can be recognized by having the buttons on their tunics spaced in threes.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] They also do not wear hackles (plumes) in their bearskins, unlike the other Foot Guards.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Since 1993, F Company, permanently based in Wellington Barracks, London on public duties, has been the custodian of the colours and traditions of the 2nd Battalion, which was placed in permanent suspended animation in 1993 as a result of Options for Change.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] F Company was formerly part of the 2nd Bn as its 'support weapons company', operating mortars, anti-tank weapons, and reconnaissance vehicles.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The regiment consists of a single operational battalion, which was based in Catterick between 2008 and 2015, thereafter moving to Aldershot in the armoured infantry role.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] 1st Battalion will be equipped with Mastiff Vehicles (and later the Mechanised Infantry Vehicle (MIV)) under Army 2020 Refine and be under the first Strike Brigade.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The 1st Battalion will not rotate public ceremonial duties unlike the other guards regiments with F Company performing that role.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Following the Integrated Review A (London Scottish) Company of the London Regiment at Rochester Row, Westminster became G (Messines) Company, Scots Guards.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] Regular Recruits to the Guards Division go through a thirty-week training programme at the Infantry Training Centre (ITC).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] The training is two weeks more than the training for the Regular line infantry regiments of the British Army; the extra training, carried out throughout the course, is devoted to drill and ceremonies.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] King Edward VII assumed the colonelcy-in-chief of the regiment on his accession, and subsequent monarchs have also been colonel-in-chief.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] For many years a Colonel was given the full-time appointment of Lieutenant Colonel Commanding the regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/3rd-foot-guards] After 1986 a Lieutenant Colonel was appointed, but in 1989 the role was retitled Regimental Lieutenant Colonel; this was an honorary appointment, filled by a senior serving officer who took on responsibility for the 'regimental affairs' of the regiment alongside his primary military role.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The **63rd Regiment of Foot** was a British Army regiment raised in 1756.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] Under the Childers Reforms, it amalgamated with the 96th Regiment of Foot to form the Manchester Regiment in 1881.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The formation of the regiment was prompted by the expansion of the army as a result of the commencement of the Seven Years' War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] On 25 August 1756 it was ordered that a number of existing regiments should raise a second battalion; among those chosen was the 8th Regiment of Foot.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2nd Battalion of the 8th Regiment of Foot was formed on 10 December 1756 and renumbered as the 63rd Regiment of Foot on 21 April 1758.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] Later that year, the newly created 63rd, along with a number of other regiments and various other assets, set off for the West Indies.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In January 1759 the regiment took part in the unsuccessful invasion of Martinique.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] Later that month the regiment took part in the invasion of Guadeloupe: after the Royal Navy bombarded Basse-Terre, the British troops landed on the west part of the island, near Fort Royal, a large citadel.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] By 24 January, British troops had entered the main town: the citadel there had been abandoned.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment suffered a number of attacks while garrisoning the citadel, the rest of the force having moved to the more hospitable east of the island.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] During one attack, the regiment's commanding officer Lieutenant-Colonel Peter Desbrisay was killed.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment remained in the West Indies for a further five years.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1775 the regiment arrived in America in response to a request for reinforcements due to the outbreak of the American War of Independence.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment took part in the Battle of Bunker Hill in June 1775, with a third attack, which ended in a bayonet charge, finally breaking the Americans.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment remained in Boston after the battle, the town becoming increasingly more uneasy to be in.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] Finally, in March 1776 the regiment, along with the rest of the forces in Boston, departed, heading for Halifax in Canada.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment took part in the Battle of Long Island in August 1776, a devastating blow against the Americans, though astonishingly, the American leader General George Washington managed to reverse the blow that had been struck against much of the Continental Army's morale in this battle soon after.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] Grenadier and Light companies of the regiment also took part in the Battle of Brandywine in September 1777 and the Battle of Germantown in October 1777.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The main force of the regiment took part in the Battle of Forts Clinton and Montgomery in October 1777.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment then moved to Philadelphia and took part in the Battle of Monmouth in June 1778.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1780 the regiment became involved in the campaign in the Carolinas taking part in the siege and subsequent capture of Charleston.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] That year the mounted company of the regiment, augmented by a detachment from Tarleton's Legion under the command of the dashing, Banastre Tarleton, attacked and captured an American cavalry unit.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment also took part in number of battles as part of the forces commanded by Lord Cornwallis over the next two years, as well as taking part in another engagement near Camden in April 1781, as part of a force under the command of General Francis Rawdon.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1782 the regiment was designated the **63rd (West Suffolk) Regiment of Foot**.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1794 the regiment joined British forces already taking part in the Flanders Campaign.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was involved in a number of actions before the British forces withdrew from the Netherlands in 1795.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] That same year, the regiment were part of a force designed to take a number of Caribbean islands under Dutch and French control.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] However, their transport ship sank, with the loss of two companies from the regiment, en route to the islands.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment took part in a variety of operations on the islands in the Caribbean, including helping to put down Fédon's rebellion in the Grenada in 1796.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] It remaining in the region until 1799, when they departed for home.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In August 1799 the regiment took part in the Anglo-Russian invasion of Holland, seeing action at the Battle of Alkmaar in October 1799.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In November 1801 the regiment joined the garrison at Gibraltar and, in 1803, it was deployed to Ireland.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1807 the 1st battalion was involved in an expedition to Madeira, a Portuguese-controlled territory, under the command of Major-General William Beresford.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] Once the expeditionary forces landed, the Portuguese Governor agreed to all demands made by the British forces.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In February 1808 the 1st battalion was stationed in Barbados.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] It took part the expedition to Martinique, which the British force captured.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] On 9 April 1809, a detachment from the 1st battalion was serving on the Treasury store-ship *Emma*, and so shared in the prize money for the French brig *Navigateur* for which *Emma* was a joint captor with sundry other ships.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st battalion became the garrison for island, suffering heavily from diseases one would expect in such tropical weather at that time.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In January 1810, part of the 1st battalion took part in the capture of Guadeloupe, a duty the regiment had participated in many years before.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st battalion returned to Martinique and finally departed the Caribbean in 1819.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] Meanwhile, the 2nd battalion took part in the disastrous Walcheren Campaign in autumn 1809, suffering from terrible fever while assisting in the capture of a number of towns on the island.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1820, the regiment were deployed to Ireland, a deployment that would last until 1826.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was involved in an expedition to Portugal due to fears of impending insurrection in the country and landed there in January 1827.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The rebel cause largely subsided, thanks largely in part due to the expedition made by the British forces.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1829, the regiment began providing escorts for convict ships traveling to New South Wales and Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The rest of the regiment became garrison troops in the latter colony.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] A detachment of the regiment was present at the foundation ceremony of Perth in 1829, and had arrived in Western Australia that same year, on the warship HMS *Sulphur*.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The officer commanding the detachment of the regiment at the ceremony, Captain Frederick Chidley Irwin, would later twice serve as administrator of Western Australia.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment transferred from Australia to India in 1833.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment deployed to Mawlamyine in Burma in 1838, returned to India in 1842, and then embarked for England in 1847.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment landed in the Kalamita Bay in August 1854 as part of the 4th Division for service in the Crimean War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment took part in the Battle of Inkerman in November 1854 and was engaged in extensive hand-to-hand fighting.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] At one point, both colour bearers fell: Ensign James Hulton Clutterbuck, carrying the Queen's Colour, and Ensign Heneage Twysden, who was mortally wounded carrying the Regimental Colour.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment also took part in the Siege of Sevastopol and was part of a force created to assault a part of the great fortress of Sevastopol on 8 September 1855, during the last day of the long siege, known as Battle of the Great Redan.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] After leaving the Crimea, the regiment sailed for Nova Scotia in 1856.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] Upon their arrival at the dockyard in Halifax, a large crowd of many thousands came out to greet the regiment, as if they were a modern-day football team.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment returned home in 1865 and then departed for India in 1870.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] As part of the Cardwell Reforms of the 1870s, where single-battalion regiments were linked together to share a single depot and recruiting district in the United Kingdom, the 63rd was linked with the 96th Regiment of Foot, and assigned to district no.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] 16 at Wellington Barracks in Ashton-under-Lyne.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/63rd-west-suffolk-regiment-of-foot] On 1 July 1881 the Childers Reforms came into effect and the regiment amalgamated with the 96th Regiment of Foot to form the Manchester Regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The **64th (2nd Staffordshire) Regiment of Foot** was an infantry regiment of the British Army.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was created as the 2nd Battalion, 11th Regiment of Foot in 1756, redesignated as the **64th Regiment of Foot** in 1758, and took a county title as the **64th (2nd Staffordshire) Regiment of Foot** in 1782.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Following the Cardwell Reforms the regiment amalgamated with the 98th (Prince of Wales's) Regiment of Foot to become The Prince of Wales's (North Staffordshire Regiment) in 1881.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In the new regiment the 64th Foot became the 1st Battalion due to its seniority over the 98th Foot.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Although the 64th Foot fought in many of the major conflicts of the late 18th and early 19th centuries, it was normally in the more minor theatres of these conflicts.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] During the Seven Years' War it served in the West Indies; in the Napoleonic Wars, its role was limited, again, to the West Indies and South America.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In the mid-19th century, it fought in the Anglo-Persian War and the Indian Rebellion of 1857, where one of its soldiers was awarded the Victoria Cross.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The formation of the 64th Foot was prompted by the expansion of the army as a result of the commencement of the Seven Years' War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] On 25 August 1756 it was ordered that a number of existing regiments should raise a second battalion; among those chosen was the 11th Regiment of Foot.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The 2nd Battalion of the 11th Foot was raised at Southampton on 10 December 1756 before moving to Newcastle upon Tyne.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] On 21 April 1758 the War Office ordered that the 2nd battalions raised two years previously should become independent regiments in their own right and on that day the 2nd Battalion 11th Foot became the 64th Foot.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Shortly after King George II ordered that the dates of seniority of the 64th Foot and the other regiments created on 21 April 1758 should be backdated to the date of their raising as 2nd battalions, therefore the date seniority of the 64th Foot became 1756.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The first colonel of the regiment was the Honourable John Barrington and it was he who decided that the facings of the 64th Foot should be black.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Almost immediately after becoming the 64th Foot, the regiment was sent to the West Indies.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Upon arrival, in 1759, it took part in the unsuccessful attempt to take Martinique and then in the successful invasion of Guadeloupe.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Participation in this action earned the regiment its first battle honour *Guadaloupe 1759*, though this honour was not actually awarded until 1909.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The regiment returned to England in June 1759 severely reduced in numbers by men drafted to other units and by tropical disease.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] On arrival at Portsmouth only 137 other ranks out of an establishment strength of 790 were fit for duty, though officer strength was almost up to strength.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Recovery took a long time and after a brief period in Suffolk the regiment spent three years in the Scottish Highlands and five years in Ireland before sailing for North America in 1768.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The first posting for the 64th in America was Boston, at the time a centre of discontent and an unhappy posting as a result.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In 1770 the regiment moved to Halifax, Nova Scotia but in 1772 returned to Boston being stationed at Castle William.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] As unrest grew the 64th took place in an incident which lays a claim to the first blood of the American War of Independence being shed in Salem, Massachusetts.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] On 26 February 1775 a supply of weapons and ammunition was known to be in Salem.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The 64th, under their commander Lieutenant Colonel Alexander Leslie, were ordered to seize the weapons.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] American patriots in Salem were forewarned and tried to prevent the 64th from carrying out their orders.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In the scuffle that ensued a local Salem man, Joseph Whicher, was slightly injured by a British bayonet.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Negotiations prevented any further bloodshed and the 64th withdrew to Boston, their mission a failure.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] On the outbreak of hostilities in April 1775, the 64th was still stationed at Castle William and remained there as the garrison throughout the Siege of Boston.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Consequently, the regiment did not take part in the Battle of Bunker Hill.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] When, in March 1776, the British abandoned Boston, the 64th were the last regiment to depart for Halifax, giving them the distinction of being the last British unit to set foot in the Commonwealth of Massachusetts during the war.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Following the reorganisation of the army the 64th, like most regiments, found itself without its flank (grenadier and light infantry) companies which had been detached to form part of the 2nd Grenadier and 2nd Light Infantry Battalions respectively.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] All three battalions took part in the 1776 capture of New York and the 64th was engaged in the later Battle of Ridgefield.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In 1777 all three units participated in the Philadelphia campaign, taking part in the Battle of Brandywine, the Battle of Paoli and the Battle of Germantown.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Remaining in Philadelphia over the winter and into 1778, the 64th and 2nd Grenadier Battalion formed part of the rearguard when Lieutenant-General Clinton evacuated the city in June 1778.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Returning to New York, the 64th took part in several small operations.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The Light company took part in the skirmish that became known as the Baylor Massacre.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] November 1779 saw all the companies of the regiment being transferred to the Southern theatre of operations.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In April 1780 the 64th was part of the covering force besieging Charleston, while the grenadier and light companies formed part of the main siege force.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] After the capture of Charleston, the grenadier and light companies were withdrawn to New York and as Major-General Cornwallis began to advance on Virginia, the 64th remained in Carolina as guard troops.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In 1781 the 64th were involved in the Battle of Eutaw Springs and a year later in one of the last actions of the war, the Battle of the Combahee River.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The grenadier company was reunited with the 64th but the light company was among the units that surrendered with Cornwallis at Yorktown.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In December 1782 the regiment left America for Jamaica.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Back in England, a change occurred in army policy, to hopefully increase recruiting, infantry regiments were given additional territorial titles.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The 64th became the 64th (2nd Staffordshire) Foot and began its long association with the city of Lichfield as the depot companies moved there and soon after began to wear the Staffordshire Knot on its uniform.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Following the defeat in America, the 64th remained in Jamaica for two years, returning to England in 1783.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Four years later the regiment was stationed in Ireland, before sailing once more for the West Indies in 1793 at the outbreak of the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] At the end of the Seven Years' War both Martinique and Guadeloupe had been returned to France under the terms of the Treaty of Paris.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] From Barbados the 64th Foot took part in the invasion of Martinique in early 1794.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] As before the flank companies were detached from the rest of the regiment but all three elements were involved in the actions in Martinique.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] This short but successful campaign earned the regiment its second battle honour, *Martinique 1794* —although as with the earlier Guadeloupe honour, it was not actually awarded until 1909.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The light and grenadier companies were involved in the capture, shortly afterwards, of St Lucia and the recapture of Guadeloupe.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] A short period as garrison duty followed and then the regiment returned to England, severely weakened by both losses in battle and sickness, mostly yellow fever.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Sir Charles Grey, commander of the British forces in the West Indies, estimated that he had lost 5,000 out of 7,000 troops in less than six months.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The regiment returned to England in 1795, before moving to Gibraltar and then Ireland, where it played a minor part in suppressing the 1798 rebellion.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Within months the 64th had returned to the West Indies for a campaign of seizing islands held by, variously, France, The Netherlands and Denmark.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The first island to fall was the Franco-Dutch island of Saint Martin.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] This was followed by the Dutch island of St Eustatius and the Danish islands of Saint Thomas, Saint John and Saint Croix.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] With the signing of the Treaty of Amiens, which restored to France and its allies all territories conquered by the British, the 64th were withdrawn to Barbados.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Peace did not last long and in 1803 war with France broke out again.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The 64th was immediately in action being part of an expeditionary force that took St Lucia, earning the battle honour *St Lucia 1803* — the award of this honour was more timely, it being awarded in 1818.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The expedition continued onto the South American mainland with the capture of Dutch held Surinam in 1804.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] A fourth battle honour, *Surinam*, was awarded — again in 1818.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Garrison duties kept the 64th in Surinam for the next nine years meaning that the regiment played no further part in the Napoleonic Wars.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] A move to Halifax, Nova Scotia in 1813 found the 64th providing the funeral guard for James Lawrence, Captain of the USS Chesapeake after the capture of the Chesapeake.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In 1815 the regiment returned to Europe to be sent to France as part of the Army of Occupation after the Battle of Waterloo.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] It was to be 1856 before the regiment found itself on active service again.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In the interim there had been a short spell in England, a long posting in Gibraltar, several years in Ireland, another six-year tour in the West Indies — where once again fever caused much suffering.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] These were followed by a short three-year tour in Canada which provided one item of note.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] On the voyage home two companies, under the command of Captain James Draper, and about 100 women and children were on board the barque *Alert* when the ship hit a reef about 100 miles out of Halifax.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The ship was refloated but in a heavy sea was at risk of sinking and was taking on water.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The master of the *Alert* decided that the only course of action was to beach the vessel but was worried that the ship was becoming top heavy as the troops and their families made for the upper deck.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Captain Draper and the troops were persuaded to remain on the troop deck despite the rising water level.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The ship was beached on an uninhabited island and all on board were later rescued.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The Duke of Wellington Commander-in-chief of the British army directed that the story of Captain Draper's detachment be read out to every regiment and corps in the army as an example of the rewards of steadiness and discipline.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The two companies were reunited with the rest of the regiment in England, serving in England and Ireland until being posted to India.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Based here until 1856 it saw no active service despite being mobilised as part of a Reserve Field Force in Sindh in 1852.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] War between Britain and Persia broke out in 1856 and the 64th, together with the 20th Bombay Native Infantry, formed the 1st Brigade in the expeditionary force assembled for the campaign.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Landing in Persia in late November, the regiment took place in battles at Reshire and Bushire.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In 1857 the force advanced inland and defeated the Persian field army at Koosh-Ab on 8 February 1857 while the flank companies were involved in action at Ahwaz.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Although hostilities lasted for a little over three months, four battle honours were awarded; *Reshire*, *Bushire*, *Koosh-Ab* and *Persia*.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The 64th were the only British regiment to be awarded all four.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Following the Persian campaign the 64th returned to India arriving in Bombay only two weeks after the first unrest had occurred in Meerut.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was immediately ordered to take part in the Cawnpore relief force under Major-General Sir Henry Havelock.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The relief force did not reach Cawnpore before the city fell under rebel control, a forced march was therefore ordered and the first clash with the rebel forces occurred at Fatehpur.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] From there a number of skirmishes took place until the force met with the rebels in a significant engagement at Ahwera on 16 July.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] It was for his actions in this battle that Lieutenant Henry Havelock of the 10th Foot was awarded the Victoria Cross.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] This award created considerable discontent within the 64th as the citation inferred that it was only due to Lt Havelock's actions that the regiment advanced and achieved its objectives.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The matter was referred to Sir Colin Campbell, Commander in Chief, India who upheld the complaint raised and voiced strong criticism of staff officers — Havelock was serving as Aide-de-camp to his father — interfering with regimental officers doing their duty.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The relief force entered Cawnpore on 17 July 1857.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Subsequently, the regiment moved to Fatehgarh and remained there for the rest of the campaign until June 1859 when it returned to Bombay.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] A single battle honour *Lucknow* was awarded to the regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] On return from India in 1861, the regiment spent six years in England, moving to Malta in 1867, then Ireland in 1872.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In 1874, as part of the Cardwell Reforms, line infantry battalions were linked in pairs, and the 64th formed a joint depot with the 98th (Prince of Wales's) Regiment of Foot at Limerick.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The two regiments were assigned as district no.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] 20 with a new depot at Whittington Barracks, Staffordshire in 1880.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] Up to 1879 the 64th was stationed in various parts of the United Kingdom, often performing police duties.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The regiment returned to Ireland in 1879, based at Templemore, County Tipperary and it was based here when it was formally amalgamated with the 98th to become the Prince of Wales's (North Staffordshire) Regiment on 1 July 1881.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was renamed The North Staffordshire (The Prince of Wales's) Regiment in 1920.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In 1959 the North Staffordshire and South Staffordshire Regiments amalgamated to form The Staffordshire Regiment (The Prince of Wales's).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] In September 2007 The Staffordshire Regiment amalgamated with the Cheshire Regiment and the Worcestershire and Sherwood Foresters Regiment to form The Mercian Regiment, in which the Staffords became the 3rd (Staffordshire) Battalion.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/64th-regiment-of-foot] The black facings worn by the 64th Foot are today commemorated by the use of black backing to chevrons and rank insignia by all Warrant Officers and Non-commissioned officers of the Mercian Regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The **Royal Norfolk Regiment** was a line infantry regiment of the British Army until 1959.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Its predecessor regiment was raised in 1685 as **Henry Cornwall's Regiment of Foot**.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1751, it was numbered like most other British Army regiments and named the **9th Regiment of Foot**.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It was formed as the **Norfolk Regiment** in 1881 under the Childers Reforms of the British Army as the county regiment of Norfolk by merging the **9th (East Norfolk) Regiment of Foot** with the local Militia and Rifle Volunteers battalions.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The Norfolk Regiment fought in the First World War on the Western Front and in the Middle East.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] After the war, the regiment became the Royal Norfolk Regiment on 3 June 1935.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment fought with distinction in the Second World War, in action in the Battle of France and Belgium, the Far East, and then in the invasion of, and subsequent operations in, North-west Europe.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was raised for the English Army in Gloucester by Colonel Henry Cornewall as **Henry Cornewall's Regiment of Foot** at the request of James II in 1685 as part of the response to the Monmouth Rebellion.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Cornewall resigned his post following the Glorious Revolution and command went to Colonel Oliver Nicholas in November 1688.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In December 1688, Nicholas was also removed due to his personal Jacobite sympathies and command passed to John Cunningham.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In April 1689 the regiment, under Cunningham's command, embarked at Liverpool for Derry for service in the Williamite War in Ireland.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Cunningham led a failed attempt to relieve the besieged city of Derry.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment briefly returned to England, but in May 1689 Cunningham was replaced by William Stewart, under whom the regiment took part in a successful relief of Derry in summer 1689.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment also saw action at the Battle of the Boyne in July 1690, the siege of Limerick in August 1690 and the siege of Athlone in June 1691.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It went on to fight at the Battle of Aughrim in July 1691 and the siege of Limerick in August 1691.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1701, over the objections of General William Selwyn, the threat of war led the English government to post an Independent Company of regular soldiers, detached from the 2nd Regiment of Foot, to Bermuda, where the militia continued to function as a standby in case of war or insurrection.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The company was composed of Captain Lancelot Sandys, Lieutenant Robert Henly, two sergeants, two corporals, fifty private soldiers, and a drummer, and arrived in Bermuda along with the new Governor, Captain Benjamin Bennett, aboard HMS *Lincoln*, in May 1701.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment embarked for Holland in June 1701 and took part in the siege of Kaiserswerth and of Venlo in spring 1702 during the War of the Spanish Succession.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In March 1704, the regiment embarked for Lisbon and took part in the Battle of Almansa in April 1707 before returning to England in summer 1708.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was then based in Menorca from summer 1718 to 1746.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was renamed the **9th Regiment of Foot** in 1751 when all British regiments were given numbers for identification instead of using their Colonel's name.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] During the Seven Years' War the Regiment won its first formal battle honour as part of the expedition that captured Belle Île from the French in 1761.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It sailed for Cuba with George Keppel, 3rd Earl of Albemarle in March 1762 and took part in the siege and subsequent capture of Havana in summer 1762.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Following the signing of the Treaty of Paris in 1763 and the end of the war, the regiment moved to a posting at St Augustine, Florida, where it remained until 1769.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In April 1776, the regiment embarked for Canada as part of an expedition under Major-General John Burgoyne and took part in the siege of Fort Ticonderoga and the Battle of Fort Anne in July 1777 during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It surrendered at the Battle of Saratoga in autumn 1777 and its men then spent three years as prisoners of war as part of the Convention Army.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] On 31 August 1782, the regiment was linked with Norfolk as part of attempts to improve recruitment to the army as a whole and it became the **9th (East Norfolk) Regiment of Foot**.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In January 1788, the regiment embarked for the West Indies and took part in the capture of the island of Tobago and in the attack on Martinique.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It went on to capture Saint Lucia and Guadeloupe before returning to England in autumn 1796.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1799 the King approved the Regiment's use of Britannia as its symbol.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The next period of active service was the unsuccessful Anglo-Russian invasion of Holland under the Duke of York when the regiment took part in the Battle of Bergen in September 1799 and the Battle of Alkmaar in October 1799.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It also took part in the Ferrol Expedition in August 1800 under Sir James Pulteney.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In November 1805, shortly after the Battle of Trafalgar, the Regiment suffered a significant misfortune: as the 1st battalion sailed for the Hanover Expedition a storm wrecked the troop transport *Ariadne* on the northern French coast and some 262 men were taken prisoner.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] *The Times* reported that some 300 men had been captured, including 11 officers (two of them colonels).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] There were also 20 women and 12 children aboard.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Crew and passengers were saved and conducted to Calais.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In June 1808, the regiment sailed to Portugal for service in the Peninsular War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It saw action at the Battle of Roliça and the Battle of Vimeiro in August 1808.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Following the retreat from Corunna, the regiment buried Sir John Moore (commander of the British forces in the Iberian peninsula) and left Spanish soil.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment then took part in the disastrous Walcheren expedition to the Low Countries in summer 1809.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment returned to the Peninsula in March 1810 and fought under Wellington at Battle of Bussaco, Portugal in September 1810, the Battle of Sabugal in April 1811 and the Battle of Fuentes de Oñoro in May 1811.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It also saw action at the siege of Ciudad Rodrigo in January 1812, the siege of Badajoz in March 1812 and the Battle of Salamanca in July 1812.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It saw further combat at the siege of Burgos in September 1812, the Battle of Vitoria in June 1813 and the siege of San Sebastián in September 1813.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment pursued the French Army into France and fought them at the Battle of Nivelle in November 1813 and the Battle of the Nive in December 1813.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was sent to Canada with most of Wellington's veteran units to prevent the threatened invasion by the United States, and so arrived in Europe too late for the Battle of Waterloo.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st Battalion participated in the Army of Occupation in France, whilst the 2nd Battalion was disbanded at the end of 1815.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment saw action at Kabul in August 1842 during the First Anglo-Afghan War and at the Battle of Mudki and the Battle of Ferozeshah in December 1845 and the Battle of Sobraon in February 1846 during the First Anglo-Sikh War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The **Norfolk Artillery Militia** was formed in 1853.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment fought in the Crimean War at the siege of Sevastopol in winter of 1854 In 1866 it landed at Yokohama, Japan as part of the British garrison stationed there in protection of British commercial and diplomatic interests in the recently opened treaty port.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment saw action at Kabul again in 1879 during the Second Anglo-Afghan War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment was not fundamentally affected by the Cardwell Reforms of the 1870s, which gave it a depot at Gorleston Barracks in Great Yarmouth from 1873, or by the Childers Reforms of 1881 – as it already possessed two battalions, there was no need for it to amalgamate with another regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Under the reforms the regiment became **The Norfolk Regiment** on 1 July 1881.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It had two regular battalions (1st and 2nd) and two militia battalions (the 3rd and 4th - the latter formed from the East Norfolk Militia).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It inherited all the battle honours and traditions of its predecessor regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st battalion was stationed in Gibraltar from 1887, then in British India.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In October 1899 war broke out between the United Kingdom and the Boer Republics in what is now South Africa.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2nd Battalion embarked for service there in early January 1900, and was stationed in the Transvaal Colony.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The war ended with the Treaty of Vereeniging in June 1902 and the Battalion stayed in South Africa until January 1903, when 417 officers and men left Cape Town for home.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 3rd (Militia) Battalion (the former 1st Norfolk Militia) was embodied in January 1900 for service during the Second Boer War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] 540 officers and men left Queenstown in the SS *Orotava* the following month for Cape Town.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] As the Norfolk Regiment, it first saw action at the Battle of Poplar Grove in March 1900 during the Second Boer War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1908, the Volunteers and Militia were reorganised nationally, with the former becoming the Territorial Force and the latter the Special Reserve; the regiment now had one Reserve and three Territorial battalions.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st Battalion was serving in Ireland upon the outbreak of the war and was given orders to mobilise on 4 August, the day that Britain declared war on Germany.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Part of the 15th Infantry Brigade, 5th Division, the battalion left Belfast on 14 August and immediately embarked for France, where they became part of the British Expeditionary Force (BEF).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] They saw their first action of the war against the German Army at the Battle of Mons in August 1914.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2nd Battalion was serving in Bombay, India in the 18th (Belgaum) Brigade, part of the 6th (Poona) Division, of the British Indian Army, upon the outbreak of war.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2nd Battalion of the Norfolks fought in the Mesopotamian campaign.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The treatment of prisoners after the fall of Kut al Amara in April 1916 mirrors what later befell the Royal Norfolks in the Far East during the Second World War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The two Territorial Force battalions, the 4th and 5th, were both part of the Norfolk and Suffolk Brigade, part of the East Anglian Division.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In May 1915 these became the 163rd (Norfolk and Suffolk) Brigade, 54th (East Anglian) Division.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The two territorial battalions both served in the Gallipoli campaign in mid-1915.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1/5th included men recruited from the Royal estate at Sandringham.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] On 12 August 1915, the 1/5th Battalion suffered heavy losses at Gallipoli when it became isolated during an attack.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] A myth grew up long after the War that the men had advanced into a mist and simply disappeared.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] A BBC TV drama, *All the King's Men* (1999), starring David Jason as Captain Frank Beck, was based upon their story.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In the Second Battle of Gaza in 1917, the 1/4th and 1/5th battalions suffered 75% casualties, about 1,100 men.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1/6th (Cyclist) Battalion was in Norwich on the outbreak of war: however, the 1/6th never served overseas and remained instead in Norfolk throughout the war until 1918 when it was sent to Ireland.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2/4th and 2/5th battalions were both raised in September 1914 from the few men of the 4th and 5th battalions who did not volunteer for Imperial Service overseas when asked.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Therefore, Territorial units were split into 1st Line units, which were liable to serve overseas, and 2nd Line units, which were intended to act as a reserve for the 1st Line serving overseas.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] To distinguish them, all battalions adopted the '1/' or '2/' prefix (1/4th Norfolks as a 1st Line unit, 2/4th Norfolks as a 2nd Line unit).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2/4th and 2/5th were part of the 2nd Norfolk and Suffolk Brigade, 2nd East Anglian Division, later, in August 1915, they became 208th (2/1st Norfolk and Suffolk) Brigade, 69th (2nd East Anglian) Division.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] However, both battalions were disbanded in 1918: the 2/4th in June and the 2/5th in May.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2/6th (Cyclist) Battalion, formed in October 1914 as a duplicate of the 1/6th (Cyclist) Battalion, had much the same history as the 1/6th Battalion and remained in the United Kingdom until May 1918 when it was disbanded.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The Norfolk Yeomanry (TF), having fought dismounted in the Gallipoli Campaign, were withdrawn to Egypt, where they were reorganised as infantry and redesignated as the 12th (Norfolk Yeomanry) Battalion, Norfolk Regiment, in the 74th (Yeomanry) Division (the 'Broken Spur' division).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The battalion fought in the Palestine Campaign at the Third Battle of Gaza (the Battles of Beersheba and Nebi Samwi) in 1917, and distinguished itself at the Battle of Tell Azur in March 1918.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 74th Division was then sent to reinforce the BEF in France, where the 12th Norfolks were detached to the 31st Division, with which the battalion served during the final Hundred Days Offensive.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 7th (Service) Battalion, Norfolk Regiment was raised in August 1914 from men volunteering for Kitchener's New Armies: it landed at Boulogne-sur-Mer as part of the 35th Infantry Brigade in the 12th (Eastern) Division in May 1915 for service on the Western Front.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 8th (Service) Battalion landed at Boulogne as part of the 53rd Infantry Brigade of the 18th (Eastern) Division in July 1915 and was present on the first day of the Battle of the Somme on 1 July 1916.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 9th (Service) Battalion landed at Boulogne as part of the 71st Infantry Brigade in the 24th Division in August 1915 for operations on the Western Front.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 10th (Service) Battalion, raised in 1914, became the 10th (Reserve) Battalion in April 1915.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] During the war, Lieutenant Colonel Jack Sherwood Kelly, a Norfolk Regiment officer, was awarded the Victoria Cross while leading a trench assault by Irish troops during the Battle of Cambrai in 1917.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In June 1935 King George V celebrated his silver jubilee.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1940, the first decorations for gallantry awarded to the British Expeditionary Force in France were gained by men of the 2nd Battalion.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Captain Frank Peter Barclay, was awarded the Military Cross, and Lance-Corporal Davis the Military Medal.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Barclay would later lead the 1st Battalion in the North West Europe campaign towards the end of the war.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st Battalion was a regular army unit that was stationed in India at the outbreak of war and was recalled to Britain, arriving in July 1940 during the Battle of Britain.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] They were part of the 185th Infantry Brigade originally assigned to the 79th Armoured Division but the brigade (including the 2nd Royal Warwickshire Regiment and 2nd King's Shropshire Light Infantry) transferred to the 3rd Infantry Division, with which it would remain with for the rest of the war.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The battalion landed on Red Queen Beach, the left flank of Sword Beach, at 07:25 on 6 June 1944, D-Day.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st Battalion progressed up the beach and engaged the *736th Grenadier Regiment* at the fortified position on Periers Ridge codenamed Hillman Fortress.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In this attack the 1st Battalion suffered 150 casualties.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st Battalion continued to fight with distinction through the Normandy Campaign and throughout the North West Europe campaign.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] On 6 August 1944 near Viessoix, Sidney Bates of B Company was posthumously awarded the Victoria Cross for his great courage in the Battle of Sourdevallee against the 10th SS Panzer Division.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Lieutenant General Miles Dempsey, the British Second Army commander, stated that by holding their ground in the battle the battalion made the subsequent breakthrough in August possible.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] By the end of the war in Europe, the 1st Battalion had gained a remarkable reputation and was claimed by Field Marshal Sir Bernard Montgomery, the 21st Army Group commander, as 'second to none' of all the battalions in the 21st Army Group.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 1st Royal Norfolks had suffered 20 officers and 260 other ranks killed with well over 1,000 wounded or missing in 11 months of almost continuous combat.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] During the Battle of France in 1940, Company Sergeant-Major George Gristock of the 2nd Royal Norfolks was awarded the Victoria Cross.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] During the battle, members of the Royal Norfolks were victims of a German war crime at Le Paradis in the Pas-de-Calais on 26 May.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2nd Battalion, Royal Norfolk Regiment, under the command of Lieutenant Colonel Eric Hayes, were attached to the 4th Infantry Brigade, part of the 2nd Infantry Division, which was holding the line of the La Bassée Canal and covering the retreat to Dunkirk.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Units became separated from each other and HQ Company had formed a defensive position based at the Duriez farmhouse.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] They carried on their defence until the afternoon, by which point many were injured and the enemy were shelling the farm.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Making a last stand in the open they were outnumbered and surrendered to a unit of the 2nd Infantry Regiment of the SS 'Totenkopf' (Death's Head) Division, under SS Obersturmfuhrer Fritz Knöchlein.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 99 prisoners were marched to some farm buildings on another farm where they were lined up alongside a barn wall.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] They were then fired upon by two machine guns; 97 were killed and the bodies buried in a shallow pit.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Privates Albert Pooley and William O'Callaghan had hidden in a pigsty and were discovered later by the farm's owner, Mme Creton, and her son.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The two soldiers were later captured by a Wehrmacht unit and spent the rest of the war as prisoners of war.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The bodies of the murdered soldiers were exhumed in 1942 by the French and reburied in the local churchyard which now forms part of the Le Paradis War Cemetery.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] A memorial plaque was placed on the barn wall in 1970.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The massacre was investigated by the War Crimes Investigation Unit and Knöchlein was traced and arrested.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Tried in a court in Hamburg, he was found guilty and hanged on 28 January 1949.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 2nd Battalion, still as part of the 4th Infantry Brigade of the 2nd Infantry Division, also served in the Far East in the Burma campaign participating in battles such as the Battle of Kohima until the end of the war against Japan in 1945.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] They served with the British Fourteenth Army, known as the 'Forgotten Army' as their actions were generally overlooked and the main focus was in the North West Europe campaign.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The Fourteenth Army was commanded by the popular and highly respected William Slim, 1st Viscount Slim.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Both John Niel Randle and George Arthur Knowland were posthumously awarded the Victoria Cross whilst serving with the 2nd Battalion in the Far East, both for extraordinary heroism.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 4th, 5th and 6th battalions, all part of the Territorial Army, served in the Far East.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 5th and 6th (City of Norwich) were both assigned to the 53rd Infantry Brigade, and the 4th Battalion the 54th Infantry Brigade.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Both brigades were part of the 18th Infantry Division.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Throughout most of their existence, all three battalions remained in the United Kingdom assigned to coastal defence duties and training to repel a German invasion and, in October 1941, the division left, destined for the Middle East.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 18th Division fought in the defence of Singapore and Malaya against the Japanese advance.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The men of these battalions, and other East Anglian battalions of other regiments, ended up as prisoners of war when Singapore fell in February 1942.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] They would remain so until August 1945, during which time they were used as forced labour on projects such as the Death Railway through Burma.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 7th Battalion, Royal Norfolk Regiment was formed in May 1939 as a 2nd Line Territorial Army duplicate of the 5th Battalion and, therefore, contained many former members of the 5th.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Together with the 5th and 6th battalions, the 7th was assigned to the 53rd Infantry Brigade, part of the 18th Infantry Division until November when it assigned to pioneer duties in France with the British Expeditionary Force (BEF).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In May 1940, it was assigned to the 51st (Highland) Infantry Division.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 51st Division was stationed on the Maginot Line and therefore escaped encirclement with the rest of the BEF during the Battle of France where they spent some time attached to the French 10th Army.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 7th Royal Norfolks suffered heavy casualties when the 51st (Highland) Infantry Division was surrounded and had no choice but to surrender, on 12 June 1940, with only 31 members of the battalion managing to return to Britain.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In October 1940 the battalion was assigned to 205th Independent Infantry Brigade (Home), then the 220th Independent Infantry Brigade (Home).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] On 14 October 1942, the battalion was transferred to the 176th Infantry Brigade, alongside the 7th Battalion, South Staffordshire Regiment and 6th Battalion, North Staffordshire Regiment, of the 59th (Staffordshire) Infantry Division.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 59th Division was one of the follow-up units after D-Day in June 1944 and was considered by General Sir Bernard Montgomery as one of his best divisions.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] On the night of 7/8 August 1944, Captain David Auldjo Jamieson of D Company was awarded the Victoria Cross for his heroic leadership which greatly helped to fend off several enemy counter-attacks in a 36-hour period.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 8th Battalion was raised in 1939 alongside the 9th Battalion with many veterans of the First World War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Both battalions were used mainly to supply reinforcements to those battalions of the regiment that were overseas.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Neither of these battalions saw service overseas and remained in the United Kingdom throughout the war as part of the Home Forces with the 9th Battalion apparently being disbanded in August 1944 when its parent unit (25th Brigade attached to 47th (Reserve) Infantry Division) was disbanded.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 8th Battalion was renumbered as the 30th Battalion and used for garrison duties in Italy during which the 43rd Infantry Brigade, which included 30th Battalion, Somerset Light Infantry and 30th Battalion, Dorset Regiment, was made to appear as a full division for deception purposes.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The battalion remained in Italy until it was disbanded in 1946.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 50th (Holding) Battalion was raised in late May 1940.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The role of the Holding battalion was to temporarily 'hold' men who were homeless, medically unfit, awaiting orders, on a course or returning from abroad.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The battalion was renumbered as the 9th Battalion in October and was assigned to the 220th Independent Infantry Brigade (Home), part of Norfolk County Division in early 1941.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The 70th (Young Soldiers) Battalion was raised in late 1940 for those young soldiers, mostly around the ages of 18 or 19, who had volunteered for the Army and therefore had not reached the compulsory age for conscription.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The battalion spent most of its time in the UK guarding against a German invasion.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] However, the battalion was disbanded in 1943 due to the British government lowering the age of conscription to the British Armed Forces to 18 earlier in the year.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] This decision was due to a growing shortage of manpower, especially in the British Army and in the infantry in particular and the young soldiers of the disbanded 70th were sent to other battalions of the regiment serving overseas.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The regiment served in Korea in 1951–52 during the Korean War, and in Cyprus in the fight against EOKA in 1955–56.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1959 the Royal Norfolk Regiment was amalgamated as part of the reorganisation of the British Army resulting from the 1957 Defence White Paper becoming part of a new formation, the 1st East Anglian Regiment, part of the East Anglian Brigade.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The history of the Royal Norfolk Regiment and its predecessors and successors is recorded at the Royal Norfolk Regimental Museum.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The museum moved from the Britannia Barracks, now part of Norwich prison, to the Shirehall and then to the Norwich Castle Museum.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Although archives and the reserve collections are still held in the Shirehall, the principal museum display there closed in September 2011, and relocated to the main Norwich Castle Museum, reopening fully in 2013.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Its exhibits illustrate the history of the Regiment from its 17th-century origins to its incorporation into the Royal Anglian Regiment in 1964, along with many aspects of military life in the Regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] There is an extensive and representative display of medals awarded to soldiers of the Regiment, including two of the six Victoria Crosses won.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] St Saviour's Chapel in Norwich Cathedral is the chapel of the Royal Norfolk and Royal Anglian Regiments.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Among other monuments it contains memorial stones to the 9th Foot/Royal Norfolk Regiment and to the 1st Bn Royal Norfolk Regiment in the Korean War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The dress worn by the Regiment's predecessor units in the late 17th and early 18th centuries included orange and subsequently green facings.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1733, official permission was given to change from bright green back to light orange facings.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] By 1747, this unusual shade had evolved into yellow, which was retained until 1881 when, in common with all English and Welsh regiments, the newly renamed Norfolk Regiment was given white distinctions on its scarlet tunics.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] In 1905, the traditional yellow facings were restored for full dress and mess uniforms.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Another distinction of the Norfolk Regiment was the inclusion of a black line in the gold braid of officers' uniforms from 1881 onwards.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] When the regiment was redesignated as the "Royal Norfolk Regiment" in 1935, it was specially permitted to retain the yellow facings instead of changing to blue.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The figure of Britannia was officially recognised in 1799 as part of the insignia of the 9th Regiment of Foot.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] Regimental tradition claimed that it was granted to the regiment by Queen Anne in 1707 in recognition of its service at the Battle of Almanza.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] However, there is no evidence that it was used before the 1770s, and it was not listed as an authorised device in the royal warrants of 1747, 1751 or 1768.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] It subsequently became a central part of the badge of the Norfolk Regiment.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] The Royal Norfolk Regiment held an anniversary on 25 April for the Battle of Almansa, which they inherited along with the regimental nickname of the "Holy Boys" from the 9th Regiment of Foot.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/9th-east-norfolk-regiment-of-foot] They gained the "Holy Boys" nickname during the Peninsular War from the misidentification by a Spanish soldier of Britannia on their cap badge as the Virgin Mary.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] ABC-Clio provides service to fifteen different online databases which contain over one million online textbooks.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The company consults academic leaders in the fields they cover in order to provide authority for their reference titles.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The headquarters are located in Santa Barbara, California.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] ABC-Clio was founded in 1955 as a privately held corporation by Eric Boehm with its first publication, *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The name represents the company's two original divisions when it incorporated in 1969: ABC stands for American Bibliographical Center and Clio Press is named after Clio, the muse of history from ancient Greek mythology.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] According to Boehm, he had always been interested in history so when he noticed that there were not many good historical abstracting services available, he started publishing the *Historical Abstracts*.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] During the 1960s, a sister bibliographic and abstract publication on American history was added, *America: History and Life*, which was considered an award-winning title.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The company entered into digital publishing with electronic data in the 1960s and in 1975, it published its first online database called *DIALOG*.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] During the 1980s, ABC-Clio expanded into providing primary reference books such as encyclopedias and dictionaries and stopped publishing bibliographic books.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In the 1990s, ABC-Clio began to provide access to its humanities database on CD-ROM.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The *Exegy Current Events* CD-ROM was named "Best Disc of the Year" by Library Journal.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 1998, ABC-Clio provided electronic access to *America: History and Life*.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] By the 2000s, one of the company's most popular products had become online databases for researching many topics in the field of the humanities.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 2001, ABC-Clio began to publish eBooks, initially providing 150 different titles to schools and libraries.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The company's reference books had won numerous awards, and the company started a series of subject-related online databases for secondary school use.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 2004, the company acquired the quarterly historical journal, *Journal of the West*, which has been published since 1962.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 1996, ABC-Clio merged with an electronic publishing company, Intellimation, which also produced educational software.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The merger brought Becky Snyder, who by 2009 had become ABC-Clio's president, from Intellimation.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 2007, it sold two databases – *Historical Abstracts* and *America: History and Life* – to EBSCO Publishing; in addition, the companies also agreed a partnership through which nine additional ABC-Clio databases would be distributed through EBSCO Publishing.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing acquired ABC-Clio for US$22.9 million (equivalent to $26.1 million in 2024).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 2008, ABC-Clio acquired the Greenwood Publishing Group from Houghton Mifflin Harcourt.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The deal gave ABC-Clio a "perpetual license" to use the imprints of Greenwood Press and publish all of its titles.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] Acquiring the publishing group gave ABC-Clio access to Greenwood Press, Praeger Publishers, Praeger Security International, and Libraries Unlimited.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] Greenwood focuses on publishing full-text reference works which are authoritative on various topics.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] Libraries Unlimited came to ABC-Clio as part of a deal with Greenwood Press.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 2012, Kathyrn Suárez was named publisher for this division, which focuses on publishing for librarians and information professionals.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] ABC-Clio databases are provided under the umbrella of ABC-Clio Solutions.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] There are fifteen different databases providing access to different subject areas.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] ABC-Clio Solutions provides digital curriculum with multimedia content, text-to-speech features, translation tools which covers various topics relating to history and the humanities.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] After ABC-Clio acquired Greenwood Press's databases, they revamped the look and feel of their interface in order to provide common access through the ABC-Clio interface.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] ABC-Clio also provided the ability to search across multiple databases through one search, also providing options for narrowing the search after revamping their interface.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] The new interface is considered user-friendly and provides access to personalized features.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] Originally publishing books by disillusioned former Communists who had fled from behind the Iron Curtain, the publishing house became known for publishing "scholarly and professional books" in the subject areas of social sciences and the humanities.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 1966, Praeger sold his firm to William B.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] Benton, an American senator and publisher and the chairman of *Encyclopaedia Britannica*.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] In 1976, it was sold to CBS, which had shortened the name to Praeger Publishing before selling it to Greenwood Press, Inc., in 1986.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/abc-clio] When the renamed Greenwood Publishing Group (GPG) was acquired by ABC-Clio in 2009, Praeger Publishing became a standalone imprint of ABC-Clio, and remained such when, in December 2021, Bloomsbury Publishing bought ABC-Clio.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] General **Albemarle Bertie, 9th Earl of Lindsey** (17 September 1744 – 18 September 1818) was a British Army officer and politician.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] He was the son of Peregrine Bertie, a barrister of Lincoln's Inn (1709–1779) and the former Elizabeth Payne.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] He had two sisters, Louisa Bertie (wife of Fletcher Richardson of Cartmel) and Henrietta Bertie (wife of George Edmonds of Peterborough).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] His paternal grandparents were the former Mary Narbonne (daughter and heiress of John Narbonne of Great Stukeley) and Charles Bertie, MP for Stamford (a son of the Hon.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] Charles Bertie, also an MP for Stamford, Envoy to Denmark and Secretary to the Treasury who was the fifth son of Montagu Bertie, 2nd Earl of Lindsey).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] His maternal grandfather was Edward Payne of Tottenham Wick.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] In 1762, he was commissioned an ensign in the 1st Foot Guards.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] He became lieutenant and captain in that regiment in 1769, captain and lieutenant colonel in 1776, and colonel in 1781.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] He became 3rd Major of the regiment 12 March 1789 and 2nd Major on 8 August 1792.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] In 1793, he was promoted major-general, and was appointed colonel of the newly formed 81st Regiment of Foot on 19 September with instructions to recruit volunteers for it.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] In 1794, he obtained a colonelcy of an existing regiment, the 9th (East Norfolk) Regiment of Foot, instead.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] Bertie was promoted lieutenant-general in 1798 and general in 1803.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] In 1804, the Duke of York recommended him for the colonelcy of the 77th Regiment of Foot, then part of the Indian establishment, noting that "the difference of emolument is of great consequence" to Bertie.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] In 1808, he became commander of the 89th Regiment of Foot after John Whitelocke was cashiered and dismissed from the service.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] Bertie retired from active service in 1809 upon inheriting the title of Earl of Lindsey from his third cousin on 8 February 1809.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] The earldom had been held by Robert Bertie, 1st Marquess of Lindsey from 1706 until 1715 when he was he was created the 1st Duke of Ancaster and Kesteven.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] The Dukes of Ancaster and Kesteven held the earldom until the dukedom became extinct on the death of Brownlow Bertie, 5th Duke of Ancaster and Kesteven in 1809, and the earldom passed to Bertie.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] In 1801, he was nominated as Member of Parliament for Stamford, where the Bertie family had once held an electoral interest, by the Marquess of Exeter, then pre-eminent in the borough.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] He held the seat until succeeding to his peerage in 1809, but demonstrated little activity in Parliament.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] Lindsey inherited the Irish title of Viscount Cullen by special remainder in 1810, but never claimed it nor was acknowledged in the title.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] In 1814, he was appointed Governor of Blackness Castle, and in March 1818, of Charlemont Fort.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] On 7 May 1794, Bertie was married to Eliza Maria (née Clay) Scrope, the widow of Thomas Scrope of Coleby and a daughter of William Clay of Burridge Hill, Nottinghamshire.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] They had no children before her death in July 1806.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] On 18 November 1809 (when he was the Earl of Lindsey), he married Charlotte Susannah Elizabeth Layard (1780–1858), the daughter of the Very Reverend Charles Layard, Dean of Bristol.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] After his death, his two sons, in turn, succeeded to his titles.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] After his death, Lady Lindsey married the Rev.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] William Peter Pegus and was the mother of Maria Antoinetta Pegus (who married Charles Gordon, 10th Marquess of Huntly) before her death on 28 November 1858.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] Charles Eliot, youngest son of Edward Eliot, 3rd Earl of St Germans); and Blanche Vere Guest (wife of Edward Ponsonby, 8th Earl of Bessborough).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] Through his youngest son, he was a grandfather of Montague Bertie, 12th Earl of Lindsey (1861–1938), who married Millicent Emma Cox (the eldest daughter of Dr.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/albemarle-bertie-9th-earl-of-lindsey] James Charles Cox), and served as *aide-de-camp* to the Governor of New South Wales from 1885 to 1888.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-5th-earl-of-leven] He was the son of David Leslie, 3rd Earl of Leven (1660–1728) and Lady Anne Wemyss (1675–1702).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-5th-earl-of-leven] His mother was the eldest daughter of James Wemyss, Lord Burntisland and Lady Margaret Wemyss, *suo jure* Countess of Wemyss (the only daughter of David Wemyss, 2nd Earl of Wemyss).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-5th-earl-of-leven] Following the death of his nephew in 1729 (his elder brother predeceased their father in 1721), he inherited the earldoms of Leven and Melville, though he did not use the latter title.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-5th-earl-of-leven] Lord Leven served as a Lord of Session from 1734 to 1754; Grand Master of Scottish Freemasons 1741 to 1742; Lord High Commissioner to the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland from 1741 to 1753; a Representative Peer for Scotland from 1747 to 1754; and a Lord of Police 1754.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-5th-earl-of-leven] On 23 February 1721, he married Mary Erskine, a daughter of Col.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-5th-earl-of-leven] John Erskine of Carnock (third son of David Erskine, 2nd Lord Cardross) and Anna Dundas (daughter and co-heiress of William Dundas of Kincavel).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-5th-earl-of-leven] After the death of his first wife in 1723, he married Elizabeth Monypenny, a daughter of Alexander Moneypenny of Pitmilly, on 13 March 1726.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-5th-earl-of-leven] Lord Leven and Melville died on 2 September 1754 and was succeeded in his titles by his eldest son, David.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] Major-General **Alexander Leslie** (1731 – 27 December 1794) was a British Army officer during the American Revolutionary War.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] He was the commander of the British troops at the Battle of Harlem Heights.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] He replaced Cornwallis as commander in the South in 1782.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] Leslie was born in England in 1731 to Alexander Leslie, 5th Earl of Leven and, his second wife, Elizabeth Monypenny, daughter of David Monypenny of Pitmilly.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] From his father's first marriage to Mary Erskine, he had an elder half-brother, David Melville, 6th Earl of Leven.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] From his parents marriage, he had three sisters, the novelist Lady Mary Hamilton (wife of Dr.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] James Walker and George Robinson Hamilton), Anne Carnegie, Countess of Northesk (wife of George Carnegie, 6th Earl of Northesk), and Elizabeth Hope, Countess of Hopetoun (wife of John Hope, 2nd Earl of Hopetoun).
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] His paternal grandfather was David Leslie, 3rd Earl of Leven.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] He enlisted in the 3rd Foot Guards of the British Army in 1753.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] He was promoted to lieutenant-colonel of the 64th Regiment of Foot in 1766.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] In 1775, before the American War of Independence broke out, he led troops to Salem, Massachusetts looking for contraband weapons.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] His advance was delayed by a standoff at a bridge, during which the colonists removed the weapons he was looking for.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] His force was eventually allowed to proceed, but found nothing of consequence, and was received with hostility during the expedition.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] In 1776, Leslie was promoted to brigadier-general.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] He fought in the Battle of Long Island, the Landing at Kip's Bay, the Battle of White Plains and the Battle of Harlem Heights, the Battle of Princeton and the Siege of Charleston during the American War of Independence.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] At Princeton, his nephew, Captain William Leslie was mortally wounded.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] He transferred in 1788 to be Colonel of the 9th (East Norfolk) Regiment of Foot to his death.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] In 1760, he married Mary Tullidelph, a daughter of Dr.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] Walter Tullidelph of Tullidelph, in the County of Forfar, who had been a planter and member of the Council of the Island of Antigua.
[src:alexander-leslie-british-army-officer/alexander-leslie-british-army-officer] On 27 December 1794, on his way back to Edinburgh, Leslie was seized with a dangerous illness, and died at Beechwood House, about three miles west of Edinburgh, on 27 December 1794.
